Thought for a second

I think you’re pointing at the real fault line.

Most discussion around LLMs is still shallow because it stays trapped in questions like:
“Is it accurate?”
“Will it replace jobs?”
“Can it reason?”

Those matter, but they miss the deeper question:

What picture of mind, knowledge, action, and society is being baked into the technology itself?

That is where it gets interesting.

My view is this:

LLMs are not just tools. They are the industrialization of a certain theory of intelligence. Not intelligence in full, but a specific slice of it: intelligence as linguistic mediation, pattern retrieval, synthesis, reformulation, and plausible continuation.

And that immediately raises some uncomfortable questions.

First question: are LLMs modeling intelligence, or modeling the visible residue of intelligence?

That seems central to me.

LLMs train on artifacts:

text
code
images
transcripts
documents
symbolic traces

But humans do not live as artifacts. We act, hesitate, perceive, improvise, feel pressure, suffer consequences, inherit norms, embody habits, read rooms, and change under stakes.

So maybe LLMs are not modeling intelligence itself.
Maybe they are modeling what intelligence leaves behind once flattened into representation.

That would explain both their power and their weirdness.

They are amazing at operating on sedimented cognition:

summaries
arguments
conventions
reusable forms
surface patterns of expertise

But maybe they are weak at intelligence-in-the-act.

That leads to a harder question:

How much of what we call intelligence is actually post hoc legibility?
And how much of it is situated performance that cannot be captured in records?

Second question: has modern knowledge work already been quietly optimized for something LLM-like?

This one matters a lot.

Maybe LLMs seem so powerful partly because bureaucracies, schools, corporations, and digital work have already made human activity more text-shaped than it naturally is.

Think about it:

goals written into briefs
progress turned into updates
decisions turned into decks
value turned into documentation
knowledge turned into searchable text
judgment turned into policy language

In that world, an LLM does not arrive as an alien intelligence.
It arrives as the perfect organism for an environment we already built.

So then the question becomes:

Did we build LLMs to fit work, or did we reshape work into something LLMs can dominate?

That is not the same thing.

It may be that generative AI is strongest not where intelligence is richest, but where institutions have already thinned intelligence into administrable language.

Third question: what if prompting is a very strange model of human agency?

Prompting assumes the human knows what they want closely enough to express it.

But in real life, people often do not know what they want.
Or they know it only dimly.
Or they have conflicting wants.
Or what they want changes through engagement.

A lot of the most important human activity is not execution of known intent. It is:

discovery
reframing
stumbling
dialogue that changes the participants
conflict that reveals hidden stakes
action that teaches desire

So the prompt-response format may encode a pretty thin model of agency:
the sovereign individual with articulable intent.

But that is often false.

Sometimes we do not need a system that obeys prompts.
We need a system that helps surface what the real problem even is.

And that raises an awkward issue:
LLMs are often sold as helping humans think, but they may also prematurely stabilize thought into request form.

Fourth question: is generative AI actually conservative in a deep sense?

People call it revolutionary, but there is another way to see it.

LLMs are trained on the already-said.
Even when they generate novelty, they do so through recombination across existing symbolic material.

So one could argue that LLMs are structurally biased toward:

the sayable
the archived
the statistically repeated
the culturally dominant
the well-documented
the legible center

That makes me wonder whether LLMs have a built-in gravitational pull toward civilizational average.

Not always blandness. Sometimes brilliance.
But often brilliance assembled from what already circulates.

So the deeper question is:

Can a system trained on the archive meaningfully generate rupture, or mostly variation within inherited form?

Humans also inherit language and culture, obviously. But humans are not only recombiners. They are wounded, desirous, embodied, status-seeking, mortal creatures thrown into specific lives. A lot of real novelty may come not just from information, but from pressure.

Models have structure.
Humans have stakes.

That difference may matter more than people admit.

Fifth question: what disappears when intelligence gets framed as answer production?

LLMs are answer machines.

Even when they ask questions, it is usually in service of converging on an output.

But much of serious human thought is not answer production. It is:

lingering with confusion
resisting premature closure
noticing contradictions
tolerating ambiguity
letting reality disconfirm your frame
changing as a result of what you learn

So there is a risk that LLMs reinforce a bad epistemic habit:
the belief that every problem is improved by rapid formulation and fluent response.

Sometimes fluency is the enemy.
Sometimes delay is intelligence.
Sometimes vagueness is honesty.
Sometimes the right move is not synthesis but distinction.

This is where I get suspicious of the phrase “helping people think.”
It may help with some forms of thinking while degrading others.

Sixth question: maybe the real unit of intelligence is not the individual mind at all

A lot of LLM discourse compares model vs human.
But that comparison may already be wrong.

Human intelligence is often distributed across:

people
institutions
tools
memory systems
roles
traditions
infrastructures
shared rituals

A surgeon is not just a brain.
A judge is not just a brain.
A good executive is not just a brain.
A teacher is not just a brain.

Their intelligence is partly in the social and institutional structure around them.

LLMs plug into that distributed layer in a new way. So maybe the real question is not:
“Can the model think?”

Maybe it is:
What forms of collective cognition does the model strengthen, flatten, centralize, or erode?

That feels much more important.

Because even a mediocre model could radically reshape institutions if it changes:

who writes
who reviews
who decides
what gets documented
what counts as expertise
how fast coordination happens
where judgment gets displaced
Seventh question: is there a category error in calling this “artificial intelligence” at all?

Maybe this is not artificial intelligence in the strong sense.
Maybe it is artificial discursivity.
Artificial semantic fluency.
Artificial symbolic continuation.
Artificial rhetorical presence.

Those are not trivial. They are powerful.

But calling it “intelligence” may smuggle in the wrong expectations and the wrong metaphysics.

Because intelligence in ordinary human life includes things like:

being responsible
enduring consequences
caring
perceiving what matters
acting under conditions of risk
staying loyal to a commitment across time
integrating experience into judgment

An LLM does none of that directly.

So maybe the term “intelligence” causes confusion because it bundles together:

linguistic competence
abstract problem-solving
agency
judgment
world-engagement
accountability

And LLMs are very unevenly related to those things.

Eighth question: does generative AI parasitize human interiority?

This one is darker, but worth asking.

LLMs are trained on the externalized traces of human inward life:
our explanations, stories, arguments, code, worries, jokes, descriptions, aesthetics.

In a sense, they metabolize the expressed remains of lived experience without having lived it.

That is partly why they can sound wise.
They ingest the language produced by beings who actually had to suffer, choose, fail, love, work, and die.

So one could ask:

Is the system intelligent, or is it feeding on the public exhaust of actual human existence?

That sounds dramatic, but I think there is something real there.

The model can imitate reflection because millions of real people actually reflected.
It can imitate grief because humans actually grieved.
It can imitate conviction because humans actually risked things.

This may be why model output sometimes feels uncanny:
there is depth in the language, but not necessarily behind the language in the same way.

Ninth question: what happens when language itself gets flooded by generated language?

This may be one of the biggest long-term issues.

If more and more of the textual environment becomes AI-mediated, then future models train increasingly on synthetic discourse, and humans increasingly think through discourse that has already been optimized for legibility, speed, and plausibility.

Then the question is no longer just whether models reflect culture.
It is whether they start to recursively standardize it.

What happens to:

style
dissent
eccentricity
regionality
slowness
difficult originality
forms of speech tied to lived worlds

Does generated language become a solvent on thick human language?

Maybe not entirely. But I think the pressure is real.

Tenth question: maybe the biggest issue is not that LLMs are fake people, but that institutions may start treating people like LLMs

This one worries me most.

Once a machine can produce acceptable outputs quickly, organizations may start redesigning human work around the same logic:

faster output
cleaner summaries
constant responsiveness
interchangeable style
less tolerance for ambiguity
more measurable communication
more decomposition into prompts and deliverables

In other words, the danger is not just anthropomorphizing machines.
It is mechanizing humans.

The system becomes the template, and people are asked to become more promptable, more legible, more modular, more available, more synthetic.

That would be a profound cultural shift.

So what do I think overall?

I think LLMs are real, consequential, and not overhyped in the shallow sense. They genuinely matter.

But I also think most people are mislocating what they are.

They are not simply “smart tools.”
They are a new layer in the history of mediation:
a machine for operating on the symbolic surface of civilization at scale.

That is enormous.

But the key philosophical question is whether the symbolic surface is where the most important parts of human intelligence actually live.

I suspect the answer is:
partly, but not mainly.

Which means LLMs may become extremely powerful while still missing the deepest sources of judgment, value, and transformation.

The interesting debate, to me, is not “are they intelligent?”
It is:

What kinds of human reality become amplified when intelligence is re-engineered around language prediction, and what kinds get thinned out or lost?

Pick one thread and we can really dig in. The juiciest ones to me are:
the prompt as a model of agency, whether LLMs are structurally conservative, or whether institutions will reshape humans in the image of the model.
